Jan 17 (Reuters) - The following are the top stories in the Financial Times. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

Headlines Citigroup misses earnings estimates (http://link.reuters.com/kyc26v) Goldman earnings fall on fixed income slide (http://link.reuters.com/myc26v) Carlyle joins M&A flurry with J&J unit purchase (http://link.reuters.com/nyc26v) Best Buy's holiday sales disappoint (http://link.reuters.com/pyc26v) Intel profit rise falls short of forecasts (http://link.reuters.com/qyc26v) US watchdog plans tougher bank risk rules (http://link.reuters.com/syc26v)  Overview Citigroup Inc <C.N>, the third-largest U.S. bank by assets, posted quarterly results lower than analysts' expectations on Thursday, as lackluster mortgage banking and fixed-income trading weighed on overall revenue.  Goldman Sachs Group Inc <GS.N> reported a 21 percent drop in quarterly net income on Thursday with its worst year for fixed income trading since 2005.  Buyout firm Carlyle Group <CG.O> agreed to buy Johnson & Johnson's <JNJ.N> ortho clinical diagnostics unit for $4.15 billion on Thursday, joining the host of companies making acquisitions as the new year gets under way.   Best Buy Co <BBY.N> shares tumbled about 30 percent on Thursday after the world's largest consumer electronics chain reported disappointing holiday sales, hurt by heavy discounting by its rivals.  Intel Corp's <INTC.O> profits narrowly missed expectations in the fourth quarter, sending its shares down almost 3 percent after-hours with the slide in global PC sales showing signs of slowing.